diagrams.title: CI pipeline

threats.title: Compromised administrator credentials
threats.description:
Administrator credentials could be compromised through password sprays, phishing or social engineering.

This could result in poisoned pipeline execution.
threats.mitigation:
Implement measures to prevent credential stuffing attacks, such as rate limiting and CAPTCHAs. 

Add multi-factor authentication or passkeys to add an extra layer of security beyond passwords.

Separate privileged accounts from regular user accounts.

threats.title: Direct access to CI/CD runners via SSH
threats.description: An attacker could steal insecure SSH keys and use them to gain direct access to the CI/CD runners. This would allow direct poisoning of the pipeline, or even hijacking any secrets that the runners and their service accounts have access to.
threats.mitigation:
Store SSH keys securely e.g. in a secret manager.

Regularly rotate any SSH keys that allow access to the CI/CD pipeline runners.

Alternatively, disabled SSH access entirely.

threats.title: Compromised third-party actions
threats.description: CI pipelines can regularly use steps in the process that install or call third-party actions. These can be compromised the same as any software. A recent example is https://github.com/tj-actions/changed-files, CVE-2025-30066.
threats.mitigation:
Implement auditing and vetting procedures to allow third-party actions.

Enable and use threat detection to detect anomalies in patterns of service operation.

threats.title: Malicious dependencies added to project
threats.description: A developer creates a benign, yet malicious package and hosts it on a public GitHub repo. While working on a feature, the developer adds their malicious package into the project, backdooring the codebase.
threats.mitigation:
Build and integrate tooling into CI pipelines as a technical control that reviews package files and identifies non-company sanctioned repositories; enforcing company policy.

Enable and use threat detection to detect anomalies in patterns of service operation.

threats.title: Improper registry permissions allow untested images to be deployed
threats.description: Developers are given access to the container registry so that they may publish POC / testing images or pull production images for debugging purposes. Container registry permissions are not well segmented and allow a developer to push images to the same registry that production images are pulled from. A developer proceeds to publish a backdoored image directly to the repository and tags as latest, knowing that it will get picked up as part of the next deploy.
threats.mitigation:
Ensure logging is configured for the container registry so that all image pushes and pulls are captured.

Do not use the same container registry for developer testing / POC that is used for production image storage.

Restrict publish access to the production container registry to only the CI/CD system.

Implement image signing that will only allow the deployment of images that have been properly signed.

threats.title: Developer commits secret to Git
threats.description: A developer commits secrets to version control either accidentally or on purpose. An angry employee with read access to the repository finds the secrets and proceeds to use them to steal end-user data.
threats.mitigation:
Ensure the company is using secure secret management techniques such as cloud provider key vaults/secret managers.

Adhere to the principal of "Need to Know" and ensure that production secrets are not shared with individuals who don't have a need to know.

Adhere to the principal of "Least Privilege" and ensure secrets only have the permissions to fulfil their use case.

Enable and use threat detection to detect anomalies in patterns of service operation.
